II.-To an audience hushed in breathless silence Aeneas tells his story. At the close ol the ten years’ siege oi Troy, the Greeks, under pretence oi propitiating Pallas by a votive offering, built a huge wooden horse and filled it with warriors. Beguiled by the cunning lies ol a pretended deserter from the Greek force, the Trojans dragged this horse into their city. Under cover of the night, the armed men descended from the horse, the gates oi the city were opened, and the whole army of the Greeks rushed in. The citizenS, now buried in sleep and incapable oi resistance, were ruthlessly butchered; Priam's palace was stormed and sacked, and Priam himself slain; and Aeneas after vainly endeavoring with a devoted band oi fol- lowers to stem the tide ol murderous slaughter, took refuge, with his father AnchiseS, his son Iulus, and a crowd oi iugi- tiveS, on the neighboring hills. III. - At the opening oi the following summer, the Trojans, having now built and equipped their fleet, embarked for their long voyage. Having no definite knowledge oi the situation ol the land to which they were to direct their course, they first sailed to the coast oi Thrace, but were there wamed to depart by a voice irorn the grave oi the murdered Polydorus. So they consulted the oracle of Apollo at Delos, but, misinter- preting the response, they next proceeded to Crete, whence they were soon driven by the outbreak of apestilence.
